.Dd @MONTH@ @DAY@, @YEAR@
.Dt IRCCDCTL 1
.Os
.Sh NAME
.Nm irccdctl
.Nd irccd controller utility
.\" SYNOPSIS
.Sh SYNOPSIS
.Nm irccdctl
.Op Fl v
.Op Fl c Ar config
.Ar command
.Ar parameters
.\" CLI SPECIFIED INTERNET
.Nm irccdctl
.Op Fl v
.Fl t Ar internet
.Fl h Ar hostname
.Fl T Ar type
.Fl p Ar port
.Brq Fl 4 | Fl 6 
.Ar command
.Ar parameters
.\" CLI SPECIFIED UNIX
.Nm irccdctl
.Op Fl v
.Fl t Ar unix
.Fl T Ar type
.Fl P Ar path
.Ar command
.Ar parameters
.Pp
This is the list of commands supported by
.Ns Nm
utility:
.Pp
.\" CNOTICE
.Nm
.Cm cnotice
.Ar server
.Ar channel
.Ar message
.\" HELP
.Nm
.Cm help
.Ar subject
.\" INVITE
.Nm
.Cm invite
.Ar server
.Ar target
.Ar channel
.\" JOIN
.Nm
.Cm join
.Ar server
.Ar channel
.Op Ar password
.\" KICK
.Nm
.Cm kick
.Ar server
.Ar nickname
.Ar channel
.Op Ar reason
.\" LOAD
.Nm
.Cm load
.Ar name
.\" ME
.Nm
.Cm me
.Ar server
.Ar target
.Ar message
.\" MESSAGE
.Nm
.Cm message
.Ar server
.Ar target
.Ar message
.\" MODE
.Nm
.Cm mode
.Ar server
.Ar channel
.Ar mode
.\" NICK
.Nm
.Cm nick
.Ar server
.Ar newnickname
.\" NOTICE
.Nm
.Cm notice
.Ar server
.Ar nickname
.Ar message
.\" PART
.Nm
.Cm part
.Ar server
.Ar channel
.\" RELOAD
.Nm
.Cm reload
.Ar name
.\" TOPIC
.Nm
.Cm topic
.Ar server
.Ar channel
.Ar topic
.\" UMODE
.Nm
.Cm umode
.Ar server
.Ar mode
.\" UNLOAD
.Nm
.Cm unload
.Ar name
.\" DESCRIPTION
.Sh DESCRIPTION
The
.Nm irccdctl
utility provides serveral options to manipulate a running
irccd instance.
.Pp
It uses sockets to do a basic IPC messaging with irccd, you can use unix
or internet domain sockets.
.Pp
The following options are available:
.Bl -tag -width indent
.It Fl c Ar config
A path to a config file.
.It Fl t Ar domain
The domain to use, specify internet or unix.
.It Fl T Ar type
The type to use, tcp or udp.
.It Fl v
Be more verbose.
.El
.\" INTERNET OPTIONS
.Pp
The following options are available for
.Fl t Ar internet :
.Bl -tag -width indent
.It Fl 4
Use IPv4.
.It Fl 6
Use IPv6.
.It Fl h
The hostname to connect.
.It Fl p
The port to use.
.El
.\" UNIX OPTIONS
.Pp
The following options are available for
.Fl t Ar unix :
.Bl -tag -width indent
.It Fl P Ar path
The path to the unix socket.
.El
.\" EXAMPLES
.Sh EXAMPLES
.Bl -tag -width 0n
.It Sy Example 1 Sending a message
.Pp
.Bd -literal -offset 2n
$ irccdctl message localhost #staff "Hello World"
.Ed
.It Sy Example 2 Connect to a Unix socket to join a channel
.Pp
.Bd -literal -offset 2n
$ irccdctl -t unix -T tcp -P /tmp/foo.sock join localhost #foo
.Ed
.It Sy Example 3 Connect to an internet IPv6 UDP socket to change nickname
.Pp
.Bd -literal -offset 2n
$ irccdctl -t internet -T udp -h localhost -p 6667 -6 nick localhost mynick
.Ed
.El
.\" SEE ALSO
.Sh SEE ALSO
.Xr irccd 1 ,
.Xr irccdctl.conf 5
.\" BUGS
.Sh BUGS
Be careful when using channel names, some shells (i.e bash) ignore the #
character. In that case, quote the command like this:
.Bd -literal -offset 2n
$ irccdctl join localhost "#bar"
.Ed
